                    <p>In our hyperconnected world, digital overwhelm has become a silent epidemic affecting our mental clarity, emotional balance, and overall well-being. A conscious digital detox isn't about rejecting technology—it's about creating intentional boundaries that restore your inner peace.</p>
                    
                    <h3>The Hidden Cost of Digital Overwhelm</h3>
                    <p>Constant notifications, endless scrolling, and screen addiction create a state of chronic stress that disrupts our nervous system. This digital noise fragments our attention, increases anxiety, and disconnects us from our authentic selves and real-world relationships.</p>
                    
                    <h3>Creating Conscious Tech Habits</h3>
                    <p><strong>Morning Sanctuary:</strong> Keep the first hour of your day screen-free. Use this time for meditation, journaling, or gentle movement to set a peaceful tone.</p>
                    <p><strong>Notification Boundaries:</strong> Turn off non-essential notifications. Choose specific times to check messages rather than being constantly reactive.</p>
                    <p><strong>Digital Sunset:</strong> Create a tech curfew 1-2 hours before bed to support natural sleep rhythms and mental decompression.</p>
                    
                    <h3>Screen Detox Strategies</h3>
                    <p>Start with micro-detoxes: 15-minute phone-free meals, tech-free walks, or device-free conversations. Gradually extend these periods as you rebuild your capacity for sustained attention and presence.</p>
                    
                    <h3>Mindful Digital Consumption</h3>
                    <p>Before reaching for your device, pause and ask: "What am I seeking right now?" Often we're looking for connection, entertainment, or escape. Consider if there's a more nourishing way to meet that need.</p>
                    
                    <h3>Reclaiming Real Connection</h3>
                    <p>Use the time freed from digital distractions to reconnect with yourself and others. Engage in face-to-face conversations, spend time in nature, or pursue creative activities that bring you joy and fulfillment.</p>
                    
